Hurricane Rosa threatens Phoenix, Las Vegas, Salt Lake City with flooding (areas with drought may benefit)
It’s rare for tropical low pressures to reach Arizona, but that’s exactly what is likely to happen early next week when Hurricane Rosa’s remaining energy pulls out across the desert in the southwestern United States, with the risk of sudden flooding.
The National Weather Service has already issued warnings for sudden floods for Monday and Tuesday in western Arizona and into southern and eastern Nevada, southeastern California and Utah, including the cities of Phoenix, Flagstaff, Las Vegas and Salt Lake City.
Rosa is expected to travel directly over Phoenix on Tuesday, and bring with it rain late on Monday.
The National Weather Service in Phoenix said in a tweet that only "ten tropical cyclones have maintained tropical storm or low pressure status within 320 km of Phoenix since 1950!
Katrina (1967) was a hurricane within 65 km of the Arizona border.
The latest National Hurricane Center models predict 5–10 cm of rain, with isolated amounts of up to 15 cm in Mogollon Rim, Arizona.
Other parts of the desert in the southwestern United States, including the central Rocky Mountains and the Great Basin, are likely to receive 2.5–5 cm of rain with a risk of up to 10 cm.
In areas without the risk of sudden flooding, Rosa’s rain can be a blessing, as the region is affected by drought.
Floods are very serious, but some of the rain is likely to be of benefit as the southwestern United States suffers from drought.
According to the U.S. Drought Monitor, just over 40 percent of Arizona suffers from at least extreme drought, the second highest category, weather.com reported.
Hurricane Rosa will first travel across the Baja California Peninsula in Mexico.
Rosa, still with hurricane strength on Sunday morning with a maximum wind speed of 135 km/h, is located 620 km south of Punta Eugenia in Mexico and travels north at 20 km/h.
The storm hits cooler water in the Pacific Ocean, calming it down.
It is therefore expected to reach the landmass of Mexico as a tropical storm on Monday afternoon or evening.
Parts of Mexico may receive heavy rain, which poses a significant risk of flooding.
“A total of 7.5–15 cm of rain is expected from Baja California to northwestern Sonora, with a risk of up to 25 cm,” weather.com reported.
Rosa will then travel north across Mexico as a tropical storm and reach the Arizona border early Tuesday morning as a tropical low pressure, which will then travel through Arizona and into southern Utah late Tuesday evening.
"The greatest danger from Rosa and its remaining energy is very heavy rainfall in Baja California, northwestern Sonora and the deserts of the southwestern United States," the National Hurricane Center said.
The rain is expected to lead to life-threatening sudden floods and clay flows in the desert, as well as landslides in mountainous terrain.
