Macedonian referendum on renaming
Macedonia's people voted in a referendum on Sunday to change the country's name to "Republic of North Macedonia", which would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that has hampered the country's attempts to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia, claiming that the name of its neighbor in the north is a requirement of its territory and has therefore prevented Macedonia from joining NATO and the EU.
The two governments concluded an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the name change would undermine Macedonia’s Slavic majority identity.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts about whether the minimum participation required for the referendum to be considered valid will be reached.
The question on the ballot in the referendum is the following: "Are you for NATO and EU membership with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
But supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is worth changing its name if it allows Macedonia, one of the countries formed when Yugoslavia split, to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because that means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgievska, 79, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said they intend to follow the result in order for it to be considered decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
According to the State Election Commission, no irregularities had been reported at 13.
But the turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters voted.
"I vote for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko are voting in the Macedonian referendum on the country’s name change, which would open the way for NATO and European Union membership, in Strumica, Macedonia 30 September 2018.
Outside the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, arranged a small stage and placed chairs in front of the tents set up by those boycotting the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to join with our heads in the air, not sneak in through the back door," Kavardarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, such as China and Russia, and become part of a Euro-Asian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, membership in NATO would lead to much-needed investment in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
"I think the absolute majority will vote yes, because over 80 percent of our citizens are for the EU and NATO," Zaev said.
He said a "yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future."
According to a survey published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Policy Survey, between 30 and 43 percent of voters planned to vote in the referendum, which falls below the minimum required participation.
According to another survey conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57 percent of participants planned to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them said they would vote yes.
In order for the referendum to count, 50 percent of registered voters plus one vote must be counted.
If the referendum fails, it will be the first serious setback for the Western-oriented government's policy since it took over in May last year.
