"The sea belongs to us": Coastless Bolivia hopes the court opens the way to the Pacific again
Sailors patrol a rig-covered naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings have a sea blue flag.
The fleet's bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon bear the motto: "The sea belongs to us.
It is our duty to recover it.”
In coastless Bolivia, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still strong – and so is the longing to sail again on the Pacific Ocean.
This hope is higher than it has been for decades now as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the international court on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
"Bolivia has the drive, an atmosphere of unity and peace, and clearly awaits the result with a positive attitude," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the decisions of the international court on large screens across the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will judge in favor of Bolivia’s demand that Chile, after years of irregular discussions, have to negotiate with Bolivia to allow them a separate outlet to the sea.
Monday’s decision is also of great importance to Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic native president who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific," he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe it is incredible that the court is judging in favor of Bolivia, and that not much would change even if it did.
The UN court, based in the Netherlands, does not have the right to allocate Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible discussions.
The fact that the decision is announced only six months after the final arguments suggests that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And the last four years may have hurt rather than promoted Bolivia’s chances.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
She argues that Morales’ aggressive rhetoric has tarnished Chile’s remaining benevolence.
Bolivia and Chile will eventually continue the discussion, but it will be extremely difficult to do so after that.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, did not consider that the Court's decision had been taken unusually quickly.
Monday will give Bolivia “a unique opportunity to start a new era for relations with Chile” and a chance to “stop 139 years of differences of mutual benefit,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – used the issue of the sea as a political crutch.
