"However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States," he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances there is no chance that we will unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a nuclear-power approach divided into stages that would lead to North Korea being rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant, as it did not reject a previous unilateral nuclear weapons solution made entirely like Pyong.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim vowed to work towards "denuclearization on the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the US has said Pyongyang must first denuclearize.
Washington has also declined negotiations to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘settlement first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose through coercion and even opposes the ‘declaration of ending the war,’” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can get us on our knees is a dream come true for those people who lack knowledge of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that U.S. leaders highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party on this nuclear disarmament issue were South Korea and not the United States, the Korean Peninsula’s nuclear disarmament would not have come to such a standstill.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different than last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s future ability to reach the U.S. mainland by missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take action for disarmament, but it said much work remains to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
